benchmark_config.jira_title: Implement/Test API: PUT /1.0/kb/bundles/{bundleId}/resume - Resume a bundle

covered: Valid Request: Numerous successful resume scenarios (TC01, TC02, TC03, TC04, TC18, TC24, TC25, TC26) and broad validation of inputs (TC06, TC07, TC08, TC09, TC19, TC20, TC21, TC22, TC23).
Non-Existing Resource: TC05 covers 404 when bundle not found.
Authorization: Tests cover valid auth, missing header, and invalid token scenarios (TC07, TC10).
Error Handling: 500 for system dependency issue (TC14), 504/timeout outcomes (TC25).
Concurrency: TC21 tests concurrent requests and race conditions.
Security: TC16 (SQL injection in pluginProperty) and TC17 (XSS in comment).
Edge/Regression: TC23 regression edge case; TC12/TC25 cover boundary behaviors.
Partial/Input Scenarios: TC18 (partial input/required fields only) and TC19 (invalid pluginProperty format) demonstrate input validation.
gaps: Pagination: No tests cover pagination handling for large datasets (though not always relevant for PUT resume).
Caching Behavior: No tests around caching headers like ETag/Cache-Control.
Rate Limiting: No explicit tests for rate limiting/throttling under burst requests.
Header Variations: While TC26 covers whitespace/case variations, broader header validation (e.g., malformed headers beyond CreatedBy) could be extended.
Non-standard/Legacy Client Scenarios: Some broad compatibility scenarios exist (TC24), but further coverage of legacy token formats or edge header formats could be expanded.
recommendations: Add tests for pagination behavior if the endpoint ever returns paginated results for related data, or when operating on multiple bundles in bulk.
Include explicit caching-related assertions (ETag/Cache-Control) to verify proper caching behavior.
Introduce rate-limiting/throttling tests to validate behavior under high request volumes and ensure proper 429 handling if supported, or document why not applicable.
Expand header robustness tests: include additional malformed headers (e.g., invalid X-Killbill-CreatedBy formats, unexpected header combos) and verify consistent error handling.
Consider explicit tests for partial update rejection if the API contract intends PUT to fully replace state only, ensuring non-replace partial payloads fail when disallowed.
